# Memory Allocation 🏗️

`malloc` stands for **M**emory **ALLOC**ation.
It reserves a block of bytes in the heap and returns a `void*` pointer to it.

```c
#include <stdlib.h>

int *ptr;
// Allocate space for 5 integers
ptr = (int*) malloc(5 * sizeof(int));
```
If allocation fails (RAM full), it returns `NULL`.

# Arrays without Limits

<!-- FULL_CODE_START
#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h>

int main() {
    int *arr;
    int n;

    printf("Enter number of elements: ");
    scanf("%d", &n);

    // 1. Allocate memory
    arr = (int*) malloc(n * sizeof(int));

    if (arr == NULL) {
        printf("Memory not allocated.\n");
        exit(0);
    }

    // 2. Use memory
    printf("Enter %d elements:\n", n);
    for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
        scanf("%d", &arr[i]);
    }

    printf("The elements are: ");
    for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
        printf("%d ", arr[i]);
    }

    // 3. Resize memory
    printf("\nExpanding array by 2 more...\n");
    n = n + 2;
    arr = (int*) realloc(arr, n * sizeof(int));

    arr[n-2] = 99;
    arr[n-1] = 100;

    printf("New list: ");
    for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i) {
        printf("%d ", arr[i]);
    }

    // 4. Free memory
    free(arr);
    printf("\nMemory released!\n");

    return 0;
}
FULL_CODE_END -->
